#compdef kit
# =============================================================================
# kit — KitOps "open source DevOps tool from the CNCF for packaging
#        and versioning AI/ML models, datasets, code, and
#        configuration into an OCI Artifact."  A model-lifecycle
#        management tool that solves the problem of distributing
#        ML model artifacts (weights, datasets, training configs,
#        inference code, serving configurations) using the same
#        OCI Distribution Spec that Docker uses for container
#        images.  KitOps lets ML teams:
#          - Pack: bundle a model + datasets + configs into an
#            OCI Artifact (a ModelKit) with a Kitfile manifest
#            describing the contents
#          - Push: publish ModelKits to any OCI Distribution-
#            compliant registry (Docker Hub, GHCR, Harbor, Quay,
#            Artifactory, ECR, GAR, ACR)
#          - Pull: retrieve ModelKits from registries with content-
#            addressable verification
#          - Unpack: extract individual files from a ModelKit
#            without unpacking everything (saves bandwidth for
#            large models)
#          - Tag/Diff: version + compare ModelKits
#          - Inspect/Info: examine ModelKit metadata + contents
#          - Login/Logout: authenticate to registries
#          - Dev: run local model serving for ModelKits
#          - Import: convert HuggingFace / GGUF / MLflow models
#            into ModelKits
#        kit is a CNCF Sandbox project (joined 2024) — making it
#        the first ML-model-packaging tool with formal foundation
#        governance.  Sponsored by Jozu (founded by Brad Micklea).
#
# Author:  KitOps Maintainers (sponsored by Jozu, founded by Brad
#          Micklea formerly Red Hat OpenShift / Eclipse Che / Linux
#          Foundation governance).  Created 2023; donated to CNCF
#          Sandbox 2024.
# Source:  https://github.com/kitops-ml/kitops
# CLI:     cmd/root.go (uses spf13/cobra for CLI framework +
#                        vbauerster/mpb for multi-progress-bar
#                        rendering during multi-layer push/pull
#                        operations)
# Library: vbauerster/mpb
#          ("multi progress bar for Go cli applications" —
#           Vladimir Bauer's Go library for displaying MULTIPLE
#           CONCURRENT PROGRESS BARS with synchronized rendering;
#           the parallel to Rust's indicatif R522 MultiProgress
#           and TS-Node's listr2 R556 task list runner in the
#           "multi-concurrent-operation display" category.)
# License: Apache-2.0
# Status:  Active — 1344+ stars on kitops-ml/kitops (CNCF Sandbox
#          project as of 2024); mpb itself is 2494+ stars on
#          vbauerster/mpb (continuous development since 2017 by
#          Vladimir Bauer + 50+ contributors).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — GO CROSSES TO 47
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# the 47TH Go CLI library variant.  Go climbs from 46 to 47 documented
# libraries (vbauerster/mpb via kit).  New leaderboard: Rust=47, Go=47,
# TypeScript-Node=46 (Rust+Go TWO-WAY TIE AT 47 — seventh two-way tie
# at 47-or-above of this round-sequence).  Taxonomy now spans 298
# cross-language CLI library variants across 72 documented languages.
#
# Pattern: 3 leader bumps (R558 clio Rust opening Axis 8 → R559 mpb
# Go THIS → expected R560 TS-Node) following 1 new lang (R557 J).
#
# This completion EXPANDS Axis 3 (PROGRESS REPORTING) within Go to
# TWO documented libraries spanning two generations:
#
#   * Gen 1 (2014): cheggaaa/pb R523 (SINGLE progress bar,
#                    2013-vintage Go progress library grandfather)
#   * Gen 2 (2017): vbauerster/mpb R559 (MULTI progress bars with
#                    synchronized concurrent rendering)
#
# These represent TWO POLAR-DIFFERENT Go progress-bar designs:
#   * cheggaaa/pb:    SINGLE-bar design — display one progress bar
#                       at a time, blocking-style updates
#   * vbauerster/mpb: MULTI-bar design — display N progress bars
#                       in a synchronized container that handles
#                       cursor positioning + ANSI animation
#                       coordination
#
# Go now has TWO documented progress-bar libraries documented —
# matching Rust's two documented progress concepts:
#   * Rust:    indicatif R522 (single OR MultiProgress)
#   * Go:      cheggaaa/pb R523 (single) + vbauerster/mpb R559
#               (multi) — TWO documented libraries spanning the
#               single-vs-multi progress design axis
#   * TS-Node: ora R524 (spinner) + listr2 R556 (task list)
#
# Go is now the FIRST documented language with TWO progress-
# library generations that explicitly target SINGLE vs MULTI
# progress display.  Rust achieves the same coverage in a single
# library (indicatif R522); Go achieves it across two libraries.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# WHAT IS mpb AND WHY IS IT THE 47TH GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# mpb (https://github.com/vbauerster/mpb, 2494+ stars) is
# **Vladimir Bauer's "multi progress bar for Go cli applications"**
# — a Go library specifically designed for displaying MULTIPLE
# CONCURRENT PROGRESS BARS with synchronized rendering.  Created
# in 2017 by Vladimir Bauer (an independent Russian Go developer)
# as a successor to cheggaaa/pb for use cases where multiple
# concurrent operations need simultaneous progress display —
# such as parallel file downloads, batch operations across
# multiple resources, or layered container/OCI artifact push/pull.
#
# mpb's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. CONTAINER-MODEL FOR MULTIPLE BARS — mpb groups multiple
#      progress bars into a SINGLE `Progress` container that
#      manages cursor positioning + ANSI line management:
#
#          import "github.com/vbauerster/mpb/v8"
#          import "github.com/vbauerster/mpb/v8/decor"
#
#          p := mpb.New(mpb.WithWidth(64))
#
#          // Add multiple bars to the container
#          bar1 := p.AddBar(int64(numItems),
#              mpb.PrependDecorators(decor.Name("Downloading:")),
#              mpb.AppendDecorators(decor.Percentage()))
#          bar2 := p.AddBar(int64(otherItems),
#              mpb.PrependDecorators(decor.Name("Processing:")),
#              mpb.AppendDecorators(decor.EwmaETA(decor.ET_STYLE_GO, 60)))
#
#          // Update bars from goroutines
#          go func() { /* increment bar1.Increment() */ }()
#          go func() { /* increment bar2.Increment() */ }()
#
#          p.Wait()  // wait for all bars to complete
#
#      Compare:
#         * cheggaaa/pb R523: single ProgressBar, no concurrent
#                              multi-bar coordination
#         * indicatif R522 (Rust): MultiProgress + ProgressBar
#                                    similar containerization
#         * listr2 R556 (TS-Node): tree of tasks, different
#                                    abstraction (tasks vs progress)
#      FIRST documented Go progress-bar library with first-class
#      container-model for multiple concurrent bars.
#
#   2. DECORATOR PATTERN FOR BAR ANATOMY — mpb separates a
#      progress bar into composable DECORATORS:
#         - PrependDecorators: appear BEFORE the bar fill
#         - The bar fill itself
#         - AppendDecorators: appear AFTER the bar fill
#      Each decorator is a `decor.Decorator` value implementing
#      `Decor(stat decor.Statistics) string`.  Built-in decorators:
#         * `decor.Name("text")` — static text label
#         * `decor.Percentage()` — current percentage
#         * `decor.CountersKibiByte("%.1f / %.1f")` — KiB counters
#         * `decor.CountersKiloByte` — KB counters
#         * `decor.EwmaETA(style, age)` — exponentially-weighted
#                                          moving-average ETA
#         * `decor.AverageETA(style)` — simple average ETA
#         * `decor.CurrentKibiByte(format)` — current bytes
#         * `decor.Total(int64)` — total bytes
#         * `decor.OnComplete(decorator, message)` — replace on
#                                                     completion
#      Compare:
#         * cheggaaa/pb R523: template-string-based bar formatting
#         * indicatif R522 (Rust): ProgressStyle.template() with
#                                    Tera-like template syntax
#      FIRST documented Go progress-bar library with composable
#      decorator pattern for bar anatomy.
#
#   3. EWMA ETA (EXPONENTIALLY-WEIGHTED MOVING AVERAGE) —
#      mpb's `decor.EwmaETA` uses exponentially-weighted moving
#      average for ETA estimation, which gives MORE WEIGHT to
#      RECENT progress updates than older ones.  For bursty
#      progress (e.g., file downloads with variable network
#      speeds), EWMA produces more responsive ETAs than simple
#      averaging.  Formula:
#         ema_t = α * x_t + (1 - α) * ema_{t-1}
#         where α = 2 / (N + 1) — N is the smoothing parameter
#      Compare every other documented progress library — most use
#      simple-average ETA or no ETA at all.  FIRST documented
#      progress library with EWMA ETA built into its decorator
#      catalog.
#
#   4. PRIORITY-BASED BAR ORDERING — mpb's `WithBarPriority(N)`
#      lets users assign INTEGER PRIORITIES to bars; the container
#      renders bars in priority order rather than insertion order.
#      This is useful for nested operations where some bars
#      represent parent operations that should appear above
#      child operations even if added later.  Compare every other
#      documented progress library — none have priority-based
#      ordering for multi-bar display.  FIRST documented progress
#      library with explicit priority-based bar ordering.
#
#   5. INDETERMINATE-PROGRESS SPINNER MODE — mpb's bars can be in
#      INDETERMINATE mode where the total is unknown.  In this
#      mode, the bar shows a SPINNING-STYLE animation rather than
#      a percentage fill — useful when:
#         - Total file size unknown (HTTP responses without
#           Content-Length)
#         - Total iteration count unknown (streaming data)
#      mpb integrates the spinner WITHIN the progress-bar
#      container so spinners and progress bars share the same
#      rendering context.  Compare:
#         * cheggaaa/pb R523: no built-in spinner mode
#         * ora R524 (TS-Node): standalone spinner library, not
#                                 integrated with progress
#      FIRST documented progress-bar library with integrated
#      spinner mode for indeterminate progress.
#
# mpb's relationship to other documented Go CLI libraries:
#
#   * Like cheggaaa/pb R523 — progress reporting (same axis,
#                              different generation + design)
#   * Like fatih/color R527 — uses ANSI for terminal animation
#   * Like lipgloss R547    — terminal cell management
#   * Unlike all of the above — MULTI-BAR CONTAINER MODEL +
#                                decorator pattern + EWMA ETA +
#                                priority ordering + integrated
#                                spinner.
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust:    indicatif R522 MultiProgress (similar multi-
#                     bar container concept)
#         * TS-Node: listr2 R556 (task-tree rather than progress-
#                     bar container, but similar multi-operation
#                     display)
#     mpb completes the MULTI-OPERATION-DISPLAY triple across the
#     top three languages, with each language having its own
#     interpretation:
#       Rust:    MultiProgress (extends progress-bar paradigm to
#                 multi)
#       Go:      mpb (specialized multi-bar library)
#       TS-Node: listr2 (specialized multi-task library)
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE kit CLI — spf13/cobra + vbauerster/mpb Composition
#
# kit's argv parser is spf13/cobra (the most widely-used Go CLI
# framework):
#
#     cmd := &cobra.Command{
#         Use:   `kit`,
#         Short: `Streamline the lifecycle of AI/ML models`,
#         Long:  `Kit is a tool for efficient AI/ML model lifecycle
#                  management.  Find more information at:
#                  http://kitops.ml`,
#         PersistentPreRunE: func(cmd *cobra.Command, args []string)
#                                 error {
#             output.SetOut(cmd.OutOrStdout())
#             output.SetErr(cmd.ErrOrStderr())
#             output.SetLogLevelFromString(opts.loglevel)
#             output.SetProgressBars(opts.progressBars)
#         },
#     }
#     cmd.PersistentFlags().StringVar(&opts.loglevel, "log-level",
#         "info", "Log messages above specified level")
#     cmd.PersistentFlags().StringVar(&opts.progressBars, "progress",
#         "plain", "Configure progress bars (options: none, plain,
#         fancy)")
#     cmd.PersistentFlags().StringVar(&opts.configHome, "config", "",
#         "Alternate path to root storage directory for CLI")
#     cmd.PersistentFlags().CountVarP(&opts.verbosity, "verbose",
#         "v", "Increase verbosity (use -vv for more)")
#
# Subcommands: dev, diff, info, inspect, kitcache, kitimport,
# kitinit, list, login, logout, pack, pull, push, remove, tag,
# unpack, version.  When `kit push my-model` uploads a multi-layer
# ModelKit, mpb's container renders ONE PROGRESS BAR PER LAYER
# with synchronized updates — `kit`'s `--progress fancy` flag
# enables mpb's full rendering vs `--progress plain` (text-only)
# vs `--progress none` (silent).
#
# Distinct from every other documented Go CLI library on FIVE
# specific axes:
#
#   1. CONTAINER-MODEL FOR MULTIPLE BARS — Every other documented
#      Go progress-bar library (cheggaaa/pb R523) renders a SINGLE
#      progress bar.  mpb groups multiple bars into a `Progress`
#      container managing cursor + ANSI line coordination.  FIRST
#      documented Go progress-bar library with multi-bar container
#      model.
#
#   2. DECORATOR PATTERN FOR BAR ANATOMY — Every other documented
#      Go progress-bar library uses template strings or fixed
#      formats.  mpb separates bar anatomy into composable
#      Decorator interface implementations (Name/Percentage/
#      Counters/ETA/etc.).  FIRST documented Go progress-bar
#      library with decorator-pattern bar composition.
#
#   3. EWMA ETA — Every other documented progress library uses
#      simple-average ETA or no ETA.  mpb's `decor.EwmaETA`
#      uses exponentially-weighted moving average for more
#      responsive ETAs on bursty progress.  FIRST documented
#      progress library with EWMA ETA in its decorator catalog.
#
#   4. PRIORITY-BASED BAR ORDERING — Every other documented
#      progress library uses insertion-order rendering.  mpb's
#      `WithBarPriority(N)` lets users assign integer priorities
#      so bars render in priority order.  FIRST documented
#      progress library with priority-based bar ordering.
#
#   5. INDETERMINATE-PROGRESS SPINNER MODE — Every other
#      documented progress-bar library lacks spinner integration.
#      mpb's bars can switch to spinning animation when total is
#      unknown (no Content-Length, streaming data).  FIRST
#      documented progress-bar library with integrated indeterminate
#      spinner mode.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/kitops-ml/kitops/blob/main/cmd/root.go cobra
# Command + PersistentFlags definitions.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a commands=(
    'dev:run local model serving for ModelKits'
    'diff:compare two ModelKits'
    'info:show ModelKit metadata'
    'inspect:inspect ModelKit OCI manifest'
    'kitcache:manage local ModelKit cache'
    'import:convert HuggingFace/GGUF/MLflow models into ModelKits'
    'init:initialize a new Kitfile in the current directory'
    'list:list locally-stored ModelKits'
    'login:authenticate to an OCI registry'
    'logout:remove credentials for an OCI registry'
    'pack:bundle files into a ModelKit OCI Artifact'
    'pull:retrieve a ModelKit from a registry'
    'push:publish a ModelKit to a registry'
    'remove:remove a ModelKit from local storage'
    'tag:create a tag for a local ModelKit'
    'unpack:extract files from a ModelKit'
    'version:print kit version information'
)

_arguments -s -C \
    '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[print help and exit]' \
    '--version[print version and exit]' \
    '--log-level=[log messages above specified level]:level:(trace debug info warn error)' \
    '--progress=[configure progress bars]:mode:(none plain fancy)' \
    '--config=[alternate path to root storage directory for CLI]:directory:_directories' \
    '*-v[increase verbosity (use -vv for more)]' \
    '*--verbose[increase verbosity]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*:: :->args' \
    && ret=0

case "$state" in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'kit subcommand' commands && ret=0
        ;;
esac

return ret
